x4freetext: The errors in the cross-section values were compounded
by errors from three sources-the measured number of
protons - monitoring, the target thickness and the
measured number of product atoms. The Errors in the
average number of protons are shown in Table 1.
The error in the number of atoms of stable products
were compounded from standard deviations of multiple
peak height measurements of the mass spectrometric
analysis, corrections for procedural blanks and gas in
.The error propagation yielded a total error in
the number of stable atoms which in most cases was well
Large errors occurred when corrections for
total background gas or Na-22 decay were relatively
large. This was usually the case for foils irradiated
with protons near the threshold energy.
Additional errors were included for the Ne-22, Ne-22(T)
and Ar-37 cross sections, arising from decay
*By authors*.We have estimated tritium decay either
by using the known 3-H cross section in Al or by
assuming  equal cross sections for 3-H and 3-He when no
cross  section  were  available. In  most  cases  the
estimated  amount  of 3-He via 3-H decay, calculated by
either method, was Less than 5% of the total, and in
all  cases it was well within experimental errors of
corrected according N.Otsuka remarks---Fe-0 to Fe-CMP.
